{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_amaryllis_ver01/data/sn88077226/00414210387/1949042001/1031.xml":{"full_text":"5\n-Ui,\nSr*.\n\\\u00abf\n&\"<r $Xq?\nWives \"Dig In\" To\nSurvive Unemployment\nBy J$MMIE N. JONES\n(NOTE: This is the first of a\n\u2022eries of articles titled \"House\nWives on Guard\" pointing out\nthe necessity of watching their\n\u2022pending during the current re\ncession and unemployment.)\nHigh wages, good jobs and high\nliving all have reached their peaks\nand now are doing the about face\nas can be seen by the continued\nrecession and unemployment\nacross the nation. Accoi-ding to\nreports from the department of\nagriculture itadds up to only one\nthing\u2014\"The likelihood of furth\ner decline in industrial production\nprices and consumer income\" and\naccording to governmental reports\nthe economic trend this year is\ndefinitely down. More drops in\nproduction, and smaller paychecks\nare seen. These predictions are\nmade in a 30 page analysis pre\npared by the department. The\nreport points out \"The tremen\ndous demand for most type of\nconsumer goods are on a down\ntrend. The back log that carried\nthem over the war period has now\nSmith and Alexandor\nCreate New Firm\nWASHINGTON, April 20.\u2014\n(ANP)\u2014Clifford V. Smith, a\nWashington engineer and build\ner with some 25 years of exper\nience, has now joined forces with\nArchie A. Alexander to form the\nfirm of Smith and Alexander,\ngeneral contractors.\nAlexander, who is a leading\ncontractor in America, is now con\nstructing the $3,000,000 \"K\" St\nelevated highway in this city. He\nhas built numerous bridges and\nstructures all over the country.\nSmith, the new partner in the\nfirm, was chief engineer for the\ngovernment for a number of years\nHe built the Aberdeen Housing\nproject near Hampton, Va., and\nhas been the chief engineer for\nthe \"K\" St. elevated highway,\nsince its beginning.\nIt is believed that is th\ne\nfirst firm of its kind to be setab\nlished by Negroes in the District\nof Columbia.\ni 1a.'-a*.\nJ. -'L\nU. of\nFT^^^E\"\"7^7 ?'W sp\ndisappeared. During the hey days\nprosperity, industrial workers re\nceiving high wages threw all cau\ntion to the wind and spent their\nwages as they received them.\nPurchases of high priced automo\nbiles, payed double the price for\nbroken down homews put on them\nby high pressure realestate deal\ners, fabulous jewelry and went\nover board in social events to the\nextent of extreme gambling. Du\nring- this period, industry was fill\ning their stock bins with large\nquantities of material required\nfor industrial use. For the last\nsix months local industries have\nbeen unable to sell castings to\nthese manufacturers who are ov\nerstocked with material. Thus,\n(continued on page 4)\nOklahoma\nTurns\nSawn igiieal\nStudent\n\"SeitOiaslic Reasons\"\nOKLAHOMA CITY, April 20.\n\u2014(ANP)\u2014Robert E. Davis, the\nfirst Negro applicant to be con\nsidered for entrance to tjie Uni\nversity of Oklahoma medical\nschool, was turned down by the\nadmissions board here recently.\nThe rejection as announced by\nDr. H. F. Marsh, member of the\nseven-man board, was given be\ncause Davis, \"failed to meet oui\"\nminimum scholastic requirements.\"\nThis was Davis' second attempt\nto enter the school. He had ap\nplied the first time last fall.\nMarsh also said the question of\nsegregation \"did not enter into\nthe board's decision.\" Davis\nwas notified of his rejection .by\nmail, \"about two weeks ago, like\nother unaccepted applicants.\"\nHowever, Roscoe Dunjee, local\nNAACP leader, said the youth's\nscholastic qualifications were ac\ncepted last fall by Meharry Med\nical college, Nashville, \"one of the\ntwo outstanding colleges for Ne\ngro doctors in the country.\" Da\n(Continued on Page 4)\nBirthday Greetings\nBennye Lee Kent, Robert Vin\nzant and Kate Dexter\nVOL. VII.\u2014NO. 65. DAYTON, OHIO, WEDNESDAY, APRIL120, -1949 PRICE FIVE CENTS\nNews of Dayton and\nSurrounding Areas\nBy JIMM1E N. JONES\nOne person was killed and two\nInjured at 10:45 last night when\na car collided with a parked\ntruck in front of 422 Cincinnati\nSt., The dead is Elzie Centers,\n29, who's address was given as\nMt. Sterling, Ky. The injured\nwere Isaac Banks, 23, 144 Maple\nSt., and Robert Watkins, 22, 150\nMaple St. Investigation of the\naccident had not been completed\nat press time.\nSTACEY TRIAL TO JURY\nA jury in Common Pleas Court\nmay decide the fate of Wash\nStacey, 422, 2413 W. Third St.\ncharged with second degree mur\nder of Edward Dunn, 21, last\nNovember 21.\nStacey contends the gun went\noff in a struggle with Everett\nRose, cafe manager who tried to\nprevent the shooting.\nPAROLE GRANTED\nAlfred R. Creager, 25, form\nerly of 709 Five Oaks Ave., was\ngranted a parole from the Ohio\nState Penitentiary by the State\nPardon Board. Creager was serv\ning time for auto theft for one\nto twenty years in March 20,\n1944 and sent to the Ohio State\nRefdrmatory. After escaping\nfrom the reformatory on Dec\n3, 1944, he was sent to the pen\nfollowing his capture in Dayton\n(^continued on page 4)\nVirginia High Moot\nUnveils Oarver PorlraiS\nCHESTER, Va., April 20.\u2014(A\nNP)\u2014A portrait of Dr. George\nWashington Carver, painted by\nWaldo E. Johnson of Charlottes\nville, Was unveiled in appropri\nate ceremonies at the Carver High\nschool near here last week. The\npicture of the famed Tuskegee\ninstitute scientist was presented\nto the school by the eleventh\ngrade students.\nThe unveiling was handled by\nthree distant relatives of the late\nDr. Carver\u2014Frank Jr., Ruth and\nNaomi, 3 year old triplets.\nSpeakers at the ceremonies were\nDr. Limas Wall, head of the sci\nence department, Virginia Union\nand Miss Amaza Meredith, art de\npartment head, Virginia State col\nlege.\nMallard Case\nGood Reason For\nStronger\ni\nIt didn't appear in the other\ndailies, but Mrs. Robert Mallard\nwho spoke at the NAACP meeting\nat the Wayman AME church\nMonday night, scathingly denoun\nced the justice of the American\nwhite man. A good many whites\nwere in the audience and they\napplauded magnificently so affec\nted were they by the poignant\nsuffering of Mrs. Mallard, and\nthe applauded when she very\npointedly denounced whiter.\nAt times unable to restrain her\ntears, Mrs. Mallard gave an ac\ncount of what took place in this\nmost truculent assault on the min\nimum of human decency. She\ndescribed how the cowardly hood\ned mob shot her husband dead\nbefore her own eyes and how she\nfelt when she was at first arrested\nand accused of the murder. Most\nof what she said, the gruesome de\ntails did not appear in the great\nfree\" American press which was\ntoo busy screaming about Mind\nzenty.\nOne incident in particular, af-\n100 Delegates at\nWMuP Conference\nINDIANAPOLIS, April 19.\u2014(A\nNP)\u2014The recent Mid-Western\nConference of NAACP branches\nheld at South Bend, Ind., had\nmore than 100 delegates from 11\nstates and was highlighted by a\nforceful stand on securing civil\nrights.\nSpecial attention was paid to\nthe Federal Loyalty order and\nthe Cleveland, Ohio post office\nwhere many Negro postal clerks\nface the loss of their jobs due\nto accusations of disloyalty.\nto run for the City Commission of Dayton.\nNAME OF INDIVIDUAL OR GROUP\nADDRESS\nI\nv.?\nter the trial, Mrs. Mallard became\na marked woman, she had to vir\ntually \"escape\" from Georgia.\nOne night she had to hide in the\nwoods to elude a suspicious char\nacter who sat in front of a house\nof a friend where she had gone.\nThe next day, a woman riding on\na bus in the vicinity who closelwy\nresembled Mrs. Mallard was mur\ndered along with a daughter about\nthe age of Mrs. Mallard's son.\nDespite the white press, the\nworld knows of how two members\nof the trial jury stepped down\nand stated that they would not\nbelieve Mrs. Mallard even under\noath, and they testified as to the\nhigh moral character of the men\nshe swore murdered her husband.\nWe hope those who missed Mrs.\nMallard will not miss the point\nof her cross country appearances,\nnamely, a bigger and stronger\nNAACP with a more active mem\nbership. Those who have not\njoined should join today, so that\nfuture Mallard cases may be avert\ned. What other logic is there?\nFather of Birmingham\nWorld Editor Buried\nBIRMINGHAM, April 20.\u2014(A\nNP)\u2014Funeral services for Will B.\nJackson, father of Emory O. Jack\nson, editor of the Birmingham\nWorld, were held recently at the\nSardis Baptist church.\nHe had been in faltering health\nfor over two years and when he\nsuffered a stroke at his home\nMarch 16, he was taken to a hos\npital where he fell into a coma\nfrom which he never regained\nconsciousness.\nI think is best qualified\nFill out and return to the Commission Candidate Editor^ DAILY\nEXPRESS, 1007 Germantown Street, Dayton* Ohio.\ni\ni\n,^'fT\n\u2022\"J i\nf.j\nv'\ni","height":"19821","width":"15102"}}
